      SPAC guy
   =20
 =20

Here is a Florida man who spent 2021-2022
=09launching special purpose acquisition companies,=09raising money from in=
vestors for the SPACs,=09stealing the money, and=09losing it by day-trading=
 meme stocks and crypto?

He really covered all of the bases of 2021-2022 financial markets. He did S=
PACs to YOLO crypto and meme stocks, with some accounting fraud and a touch=
 of Ponzi. I don=E2=80=99t think there is any Elon Musk connection but othe=
rwise this is maybe the most Money Stuff story I have ever mentioned in Mon=
ey Stuff.=C2=A0Here=E2=80=99s  how federal prosecutors tell it:

COOPER MORGENTHAU, the former chief financial officer of two special purpos=
e acquisition companies (=E2=80=9CSPAC-1=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9CSPAC-2=E2=80=
=9D), pled guilty to one count of wire fraud in connection with a scheme to=
 embezzle more than $5 million from the two companies. =C2=A0=E2=80=A6
Between in or about June 2021 and in or about August 2022, MORGENTHAU, who =
was the CFO of SPAC-1 and SPAC-2, embezzled more than $5 million from the t=
wo companies. =C2=A0 SPAC-1 had recently had its initial public offering, w=
hile SPAC-2 was raising money from private investors in preparation for its=
 anticipated IPO. =C2=A0MORGENTHAU used the embezzled funds to trade equiti=
es and options of so-called =E2=80=9Cmeme stocks=E2=80=9D and cryptocurrenc=
ies, losing almost all of the money that he stole. =C2=A0To conceal and fac=
ilitate his embezzlement from SPAC-1, MORGENTHAU fabricated bank statements=
, which he provided to SPAC-1=E2=80=99s accountant and auditor; made and ca=
used to be made material misstatements in SPAC-1=E2=80=99s public filings w=
ith the Securities and Exchange Commission (=E2=80=9CSEC=E2=80=9D); and tra=
nsferred some of SPAC-2=E2=80=99s funds to SPAC-1 to cover up the funds he =
had misappropriated from SPAC-1.=C2=A0

And:
COOPER MORGENTHAU, the defendant, used the funds that he embezzled from SPA=
C- 1 in or about June 2021 to trade securities in his personal brokerage ac=
counts, including options and equities of what are commonly called "meme st=
ocks " like AMC Entertainment Holdings, Inc.,=C2=A0GameStop Corp., and Clov=
er Health Investments=C2=A0Corp. MORGENTHAU=E2=80=99s trading resulted in l=
osses of over approximately $1 million, all of the money he had embezzled t=
hat month.
Ah. Here is  the Securities and Exchange Commission=E2=80=99s version, whic=
h names the SPACs; the public one is African Gold Acquisition Corp., which =
is still hunting for an acquisition.
  [7]
 I suppose it will make you feel better about the SPAC structure to learn M=
orgenthau  was=C2=A0not=C2=A0able to steal the money that African Gold rais=
ed from public investors, just the other money:

African Gold=E2=80=99s stock began trading publicly on the New York Stock E=
xchange on February 26, 2021. Its initial public offering of securities rai=
sed approximately $414 million from investors, all of which was placed in a=
 trust account to which Morgenthau did not have access. But Morgenthau did =
have access to African Gold=E2=80=99s operating bank account, which immedia=
tely after the initial public offering of securities, held approximately $1=
.5 million. This money was intended to fund African Gold=E2=80=99s efforts =
to identify and acquire a company in the gold mining industry. As African G=
old=E2=80=99s CFO, Morgenthau had authority to make deposits into and withd=
rawals from this bank account to further African Gold=E2=80=99s efforts to =
acquire such a company.=C2=A0
On June 4, 2021, Morgenthau transferred $36,700 from the African Gold opera=
ting bank account to one of his personal brokerage accounts to fund trading=
 in meme stocks. Similarly, on June 15, 2021, Morgenthau transferred $25,00=
0 from the African Gold operating bank account to his own checking account =
for personal expenses wholly unrelated to African Gold. These were the firs=
t in a series of 34 withdrawals that Morgenthau made during June and July 2=
021, each below a $50,000 threshold that would have triggered secondary rev=
iew and approval by an African Gold board member. In all, Morgenthau transf=
erred more than $1.2 million during this time to his personal bank and brok=
erage accounts, leaving African Gold with just $100 in its operating bank a=
ccount by July 29, 2021.

And then he launched some new SPACs to raise money to cover up the money he=
 stole from his old SPAC, and also to blow on crypto trading:

To cover his losses, Morgenthau raised money by soliciting investors to hel=
p launch another series of SPACs: Strategic Metals Acquisition Corp. I and =
Strategic Metals Acquisition Corp. II (together, =E2=80=9CStrategic Metals=
=E2=80=9D). From at least July 2021 through at least July 2022, Morgenthau =
raised approximately $4.7 million from investors in Strategic Metals, all o=
f which he misappropriated for himself.
Morgenthau deposited some of the money he raised for Strategic Metals into =
African Gold=E2=80=99s bank account in order to conceal his embezzlement fr=
om African Gold and its accountants and auditor. For example, Morgenthau de=
posited more than half a million dollars of=C2=A0Strategic Metals=E2=80=99 =
funds into African Gold=E2=80=99s bank account on December 31, 2021, becaus=
e he knew that African Gold=E2=80=99s auditor would confirm the account bal=
ance as of that date, in connection with African Gold=E2=80=99s year-end au=
dit. Almost immediately thereafter, Morgenthau began withdrawing the money =
from African Gold=E2=80=99s bank account and used most of it to trade crypt=
o asset securities.

Just living 2021 to the fullest.

