<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Structure</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A stereotype about=C2=A0private tech investing=
 is that companies are not supposed to do down rounds. If you are a tech st=
artup, and you raise some money from venture capitalists at a $250 million =
valuation, and then a year later you want to raise more money, you had bett=
er have a $500 million=C2=A0valuation. If the market is tough, $250 million=
, I guess. But if you go out to raise money at a $150 million valuation, af=
ter previously raising at a $250 million valuation, that is very bad. Ventu=
re investors want growth, they want positive momentum,=C2=A0they do not wan=
t a=C2=A0<em>discount</em>. If your valuation has gone down, that=E2=80=99s=
 a bad sign for your future.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is mostly just a set of social convention=
s. Public companies don=E2=80=99t work this way: If they want to raise mone=
y, they sell stock at whatever their stock price is. It would be somewhat s=
illy for a public company to say =E2=80=9Cwe can=E2=80=99t raise money by s=
elling stock because our stock price is lower than it was six months ago,=
=E2=80=9D or for a mutual fund to say =E2=80=9Cwe can=E2=80=99t buy your st=
ock because the price has gone down.=E2=80=9D But in private markets it=E2=
=80=99s a thing.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One reason it=E2=80=99s a thing has to do with=
 the accounting conventions of the venture capitalists themselves. If your =
VCs invested at a $250 million valuation, and you do a new round at a $150 =
million valuation, then they have to write down their investment=C2=A0by 40=
%. They have to tell their own investors that they lost money for them; the=
ir assets under management have gone down and they can=E2=80=99t charge as =
much in fees. They would prefer for their investments only to go up.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One cynical way to understand private investin=
g generally is that private investment firms =E2=80=94=C2=A0venture capital=
, private equity, private real estate, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0charge=C2=A0thei=
r customers high fees for the service of avoiding the=C2=A0<em>visible=C2=
=A0</em>volatility of public markets. If you invest in stocks, sometimes th=
ey go up, and other times they go down. If you invest in private assets, th=
ey don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0<em>trade</em>; sometimes they go up (because compani=
es raise new rounds of capital at higher prices), but=C2=A0the companies an=
d the investment managers take pains to keep them from going down. This mak=
es the chart of returns look much nicer =E2=80=94=C2=A0it mostly=C2=A0goes =
up smoothly =E2=80=94=C2=A0so the private investment managers can charge hi=
gher fees. We talk about this theory from <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloo=
mbergbusiness.com/click/30154092.261520/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9=
vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTktMTItMjAveW91LWQtcGF5LW5vdC10by1zZWUteW91ci1zdG=
9jay1wcmljZT9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMTA0MjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0b=
V9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzAxMDQmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1=
ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd9e9fd7f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"=
itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none=
 !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border=
-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  time</a> to <a href=3D"htt=
ps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30154092.261520/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cu=
Ymxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMTEtMDEvcGVvcGxlLXdpbGwtcGF=
5LWZvci1pbGxpcXVpZGl0eT9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMTA0MjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPW=
VtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzAxMDQmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduP=
W1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBbd591774" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" it=
emscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decor=
ation: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000=
000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  time</a> around=
 here.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On the other hand, when interest rates go up a=
nd public tech valuations go down, that probably=C2=A0<em>is=C2=A0</em>bad =
for the value of a lot of tech startups. If you are a tech startup, and you=
 raised money during a boom, and now there is a bust, and you need more mon=
ey, you have a problem. You don=E2=80=99t want to raise money at a lower va=
luation, but you need money and=C2=A0your valuation is lower.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One solution to the problem of down rounds=C2=
=A0is what is called, in venture capital and tech circles, =E2=80=9Cstructu=
re.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9CStructure=E2=80=9D in this sense is generally a pejor=
ative term. If you go on Twitter and search for =E2=80=9Cstructure=E2=80=9D=
 you will find venture-capital thought leaders sternly warning founders to =
avoid structure, to accept a flat or even a down round instead of incurring=
 the dreaded structure. What structure=C2=A0means is that, if a startup nee=
ds to raise money and its valuation has gone down, it will raise money at t=
he same (or higher)=C2=A0<em>headline</em> valuation as its previous round,=
 but it will promise investors some goodies to get them to invest. Frequent=
ly=C2=A0the goodies =E2=80=94=C2=A0the structure =E2=80=94=C2=A0come in the=
 form of a=C2=A0<em>liquidation preference</em>, a promise to give the new =
investors their money back, plus some guaranteed minimum profit, before the=
 earlier investors get anything.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So if you previously raised a Series C round=
=C2=A0by selling common stock at a $250 million valuation, now you might do=
 a Series D where you sell preferred stock at a $250 million valuation but =
a 2x liquidation preference.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1=
" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-=
width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !import=
ant; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>=C2=A0What this means is:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If the company ends up being sold=C2=
=A0for $1 billion,<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D=
"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px=
; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; backg=
round-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a> the Series C common and=C2=A0Series D preferred investors will both ge=
t back $4 for every $1 they put in, because the stock is up 300% from where=
 they bought it (at a $250 million valuation).</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-b=
ottom: 5px;">If the company ends up going to zero, the Series C and Series =
D investors will both get zero.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If=
 the company ends up being sold for $300 million, the Series D investors wi=
ll get back $2 for every $1 they put in, even though the stock is only up 2=
0% from where they bought it, because of that 2x liquidation preference. Th=
e 2x liquidation preference just means that the Series D investors get back=
 twice their money before any of the common investors get anything. Meanwhi=
le the Series=C2=A0C common investors should get back $1.20 for every $1 th=
ey put in (because the stock is up 20% from where they bought it), but in p=
ractice they will get less, because the Series D investors get paid first o=
ut of the proceeds.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; ba=
ckground-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>
</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If the company ends up being sold=
 for $100 million, the Series D investors will get back $2 for every $1 the=
y put in, as long as they put in less than $50 million. Meanwhile the Serie=
s C investors will have a huge, perhaps total, loss.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The preferred stock has the same=C2=A0<em>upsi=
de=C2=A0</em>as the common stock, but it has a lot of protection on the=C2=
=A0<em>downside</em>.=C2=A0If the company=E2=80=99s valuation ends up being=
 modestly down, or flat, or even modestly up, the preferred stock still mak=
es its guaranteed return.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This preferred stock should obviously be more =
attractive to investors than the common stock: It has the same returns if t=
hings work out, but less risk if they don=E2=80=99t. You can, using somewha=
t hand-wavy but reasonable assumptions and a standard option pricing model,=
<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-4" style=3D"color: #000000; t=
ext-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-co=
lor: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: trans=
parent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a> assign a=C2=A0<em>value=C2=A0</em>to that difference; you can say =E2=
=80=9Cif the common stock is worth $1 per share then the preferred should b=
e worth $1.20 per share=E2=80=9D or whatever. And then, if you think about =
it for a bit, you can say: =E2=80=9CWell this company didn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0<=
em>really=C2=A0</em>raise money at a $250 million valuation, did it? That l=
iquidation preference is worth something, around $0.20 per share, so=C2=A0<=
em>really=C2=A0</em>it raised at like $208 million per share;=C2=A0<em>real=
ly=C2=A0</em>this <em>was </em>a down round.=E2=80=9D But that is viewed as=
 a somewhat esoteric and annoying thing to say. =E2=80=9CNo,=E2=80=9D peopl=
e will reply; =E2=80=9Cit raised at a $250 million valuation, but with stru=
cture.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">(In fact there is a <a href=3D"https://link.ma=
il.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30154092.261520/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJn=
LmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTctMDgtMDMvYml0Y29pbi1mb3Jrcy1hbmQtdW5pY29=
ybi1mYWtlcz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMTA0MjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV=
9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzAxMDQmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1Z=
mY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB1828b761" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"i=
temscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none =
!important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-=
bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  well-known</a> 2017 paper a=
bout tech unicorn valuations, =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombe=
rgbusiness.com/click/30154092.261520/aHR0cHM6Ly9wYXBlcnMuc3Nybi5jb20vc29sMy=
9wYXBlcnMuY2ZtP2Fic3RyYWN0X2lkPTI5NTU0NTU/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBaed1f720=
" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D=
"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px=
; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-colo=
r: #ccc;">Squaring Venture Capital Valuations with Reality</a>,=E2=80=9D=C2=
=A0in which Will Gornall and Ilya Strebulaev quantified the value of liquid=
ation preferences and other structural terms in big private tech companies.=
 =E2=80=9CWe value unicorns using financial terms from legal filings and fi=
nd that reported unicorn post-money valuations average 48% above fair value=
, with 14 being more than 100% above,=E2=80=9D they wrote: The headline val=
uations overstate the companies=E2=80=99 value, because they don=E2=80=99t =
attribute any value to the structure. Everyone nodded politely at this resu=
lt and said =E2=80=9Cyes that is completely correct,=E2=80=9D then went bac=
k to quoting the headline valuations.)</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway, this is all most widely discussed in t=
he field of tech startups, but the basic issue is more widespread: The attr=
action of private investments is that they=C2=A0<em>don=E2=80=99t have to g=
o down when the market goes down</em>. With any particular private investme=
nt, it is possible that this is because the investment manager is just so g=
ood at investing that she manages to invest in things that don=E2=80=99t go=
 down. But as a general matter, the explanation is that private investments=
=C2=A0<em>don=E2=80=99t trade</em>, and so when the market sells off, they =
don=E2=80=99t. Sometimes, though, in order to maintain that attraction, you=
 need some structure.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So for instance Blackstone Inc. manages a larg=
e non-traded real estate fund called the Blackstone Real Estate Income Trus=
t, or BREIT. In December Blackstone <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergb=
usiness.com/click/30154092.261520/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYnJlaXQuY29tL3dwLWNvbnRlb=
nQvdXBsb2Fkcy9zaXRlcy8zMy8yMDIyLzEyL05vdmVtYmVyLTIwMjItUGVyZm9ybWFuY2UtRkFR=
LnBkZj92PTE2NzExNDMxMjQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe1ebddcf" itemprop=3D"Stor=
yLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; t=
ext-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-co=
lor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> put out=
 a report</a> noting that BREIT =E2=80=9Chas produced an +8.4% net return=
=E2=80=9D in the 11 months through November 2022, even as publicly traded r=
eal estate investment trusts were down more than 20%.<a class=3D"footnote-i=
ndex" href=3D"#footnote-5" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !=
important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-b=
ottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; dis=
play: inline-block;">
<span>[5]</span>
</a> Possible explanations for that outperformance include (1) BREIT has mu=
ch better assets and cash flows than public REITs (Blackstone=E2=80=99s exp=
lanation) and/or (2) public REITs have trading prices, and they went down i=
n the broad market selloff, but BREIT doesn=E2=80=99t trade. The market doe=
sn=E2=80=99t decide BREIT=E2=80=99s price each day;=C2=A0Blackstone does.</=
p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also in December, Blackstone limited redemptio=
ns at BREIT; <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30154=
092.261520/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMTIt=
MDEvYmxhY2tzdG9uZS1yZWFsLWVzdGF0ZS1mdW5kLXRvcHMtbGltaXQtZm9yLXJlZGVtcHRpb24=
tcmVxdWVzdHM_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDEwNDIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG=
1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwMTA0JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0d=
WZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB03571ebb" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"=
itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none=
 !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border=
-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  Bloomberg reported on Dec.=
 1</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Blackstone Real Estate Income Trust Inc. has b=
een facing withdrawal requests exceeding its quarterly limit, a major test =
for the one of the private equity firm=E2=80=99s most ambitious efforts to =
reach individual investors. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Unlike many real estate investment trusts, BRE=
IT=E2=80=99s shares don=E2=80=99t trade on exchanges. It has thresholds on =
how much money investors can take out to avoid forced selling. This means i=
f too many people head for the exits, its fund board can opt to restrict wi=
thdrawals or raise its limits. BREIT said requests have exceeded the 2% of =
the net asset value monthly limit and 5% of the quarterly threshold.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you are a BREIT investor, and you think tha=
t BREIT=E2=80=99s value has held up because it has better assets and cash f=
lows than public REITs, you should probably keep your money at BREIT. But i=
f=C2=A0you think that BREIT=E2=80=99s value has held up better than that of=
 public REITs just because Blackstone has been slow to mark it down =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0if you think that BREIT=E2=80=99s valuation is stale =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0then=C2=A0you might be tempted to take your money out at that stale valu=
ation. A lot of people were apparently tempted.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But then yesterday BREIT announced =E2=80=A6=
=C2=A0a new fundraising round with structure? <a href=3D"https://link.mail.=
bloombergbusiness.com/click/30154092.261520/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmN=
vbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDEtMDMvYmxhY2tzdG9uZS1zLWJyZWl0LWdldHMtNC1iaW=
xsaW9uLWZyb20tdW5pdmVyc2l0eS1vZi1jYWxpZm9ybmlhP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAxMDQyM19NT05FW=
VNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIz=
MDEwNCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB3de931ab" i=
temprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"co=
lor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; b=
order-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: =
#ccc;">  Bloomberg reports</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Blackstone Inc. is getting a $4 billion cash i=
nfusion from the University of California for its massive real estate fund =
Blackstone Real Estate Income Trust, which is facing heightened pressure fr=
om investors pulling cash.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">UC Investments will invest the $4 billion in t=
he Class I common shares, according to a statement on Tuesday. The deal wil=
l give the $68 billion BREIT a longer-term source of capital. In exchange, =
the agreement ensures that the University of California nabs a minimum annu=
alized net return of 11.25% over the six-year holding period of its investm=
ent thanks to a $1 billion backstop from Blackstone. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The deal is =E2=80=9Ca massive affirmation of =
the quality of the portfolio we have constructed, of the values of the asse=
ts here and the performance outlook,=E2=80=9D Jon Gray, Blackstone=E2=80=99=
s president, said on Bloomberg Television.=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Well. Yes. There is that $1 billion backstop, =
though,=C2=A0that guaranteed return. Here is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.b=
loombergbusiness.com/click/30154092.261520/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxhY2tzdG9uZS5j=
b20vbmV3cy9wcmVzcy91Yy1pbnZlc3RtZW50cy1jcmVhdGVzLXN0cmF0ZWdpYy12ZW50dXJlLXd=
pdGgtYmxhY2tzdG9uZS10by1pbnZlc3QtNC1iaWxsaW9uLWluLWJyZWl0LWNvbW1vbi1zaGFyZX=
Mv/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB21d8a7de" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"i=
temscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none =
!important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-=
bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Blackstone=E2=80=99s press r=
elease</a> announcing the deal:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This strategic venture is being formed through=
 a two-part transaction whereby UC Investments will acquire $4 billion of B=
REIT Class I common shares at the January 1, 2023 public offering price wit=
h fees and terms consistent with existing BREIT shareholders. UC Investment=
s will have the option to redeem its investment ratably over two years afte=
r January 2028 (an effective 6-year hold). Outside of the long-term nature =
of this investment, the Class I common shares to be acquired by UC Investme=
nts will be no different from any other outstanding Class I common shares.<=
/p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In addition, Blackstone and UC Investments hav=
e entered into a separate strategic agreement that provides for a waterfall=
 structure with respect to the total return to be received by UC Investment=
s on its investment in the Class I common shares. As part of the agreement,=
 Blackstone will contribute $1 billion of its current holdings in BREIT to =
support an 11.25% minimum annualized net return for UC Investments over the=
 effective 6-year hold period. In exchange, Blackstone will be entitled to =
receive an incremental 5% cash promote payment from UC Investments on any r=
eturns received in excess of the specified minimum, in addition to the exis=
ting management and incentive fees borne by all holders of Class I shares o=
f BREIT.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">UC Investments is buying $4 billion of BREIT c=
ommon stock at the same price as BREIT=E2=80=99s other investors, and with =
a sixish-year lockup: As a matter of=C2=A0<em>headline valuation</em>, UC i=
s providing =E2=80=9Ca massive affirmation =E2=80=A6=C2=A0of the values of =
the assets here.=E2=80=9D But Blackstone =E2=80=94=C2=A0which owns a bunch =
of BREIT shares itself =E2=80=94=C2=A0is effectively kicking in $1 billion =
of those shares to guarantee UC=E2=80=99s returns. If BREIT returns 11.25% =
or 15% or 25% annualized=C2=A0over the next six years, then UC Investments =
and all of BREIT=E2=80=99s other investors will get 11.25% or 15% or 25%; i=
n fact UC Investments will get a bit less, because it will pay an extra 5% =
of those returns to Blackstone. But if BREIT returns 9% or 10%, UC Investme=
nts will still get 11.25%, because Blackstone will pay it the difference, u=
p to $1 billion.=C2=A0If BREIT returns 0% or -10%, UC Investments will get =
less =E2=80=94=C2=A0$1 billion only covers so much=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0but =
it will do better than BREIT=E2=80=99s other investors. Basically if things=
 go well at BREIT, UC Investments will get almost the same upside as other =
investors, though it will give up about 5% of it; if things go poorly, then=
 Blackstone will end up paying UC Investments $1 billion for this $4 billio=
n investment. Bloomberg <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/=
click/30154092.261520/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzL=
zIwMjMtMDEtMDMvYmxhY2tzdG9uZS1kYW5nbGVzLWJhY2tzdG9wLXRvLXN3ZWV0ZW4tNC1iaWxs=
aW9uLWJyZWl0LWRlYWw_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDEwNDIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWF=
pbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwMTA0JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb2=
5leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBacfebc2f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemsc=
ope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoratio=
n: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000;=
 border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  also reports</a>:</=
p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The deal, coming at a time when commercial rea=
l estate valuations are declining amid soaring borrowing costs, is a warnin=
g signal that big investors will demand more protections to bet on property=
 investments. =C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CIn our view, the transaction provides=
 a negative read-through to the commercial real estate sector based on a hi=
gher cost of capital,=E2=80=9D Jade Rahmani and Michael Brown, analysts wit=
h Keefe, Bruyette &amp; Woods, wrote in a note.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Yes but that is the esoteric annoying view. Th=
e headline is that UC Investments is buying BREIT at its current offering p=
rice.</p>
